entry.title: Fenced frame: Add WPT for _unfencedTop automatic beacons.
entry.content:
There are already WPTs in place to test the '_blank' navigation

automatic beacon case. This CL adds a test to check the '_unfencedTop'

path. This is set up differently than other tests because an

'_unfencedTop' navigation replaces the top-level page that navigates it,

which causes any tests running in the old page to be unloaded. Instead,

we move the actual test to the page that the '_unfencedTop' navigation

navigates to, and use the initial page as simply a way to set up the

test.

nullopt size and allow CalculateOffsets to fail to compute offsets. If

entry.title: [QuickStart] Delay creation of utility process.
entry.content:
We should delay the creation of the Nearby Connections utility process

until it is going to be used. For Quick Start the process is created

when we start advertising via the NearbyConnectionsManager, or when we

acquire a SharedRemote for the QuickStartDecoder (since the receiver

lives in the utility process).



We previously spun up the utility process as soon as the Welcome Screen

loaded in OOBE, before the user has interacted with the feature. This

happened when we acquired a QuickStartDecoder to inject it as a

dependency of the TargetDeviceBootstrapController.



With this change we just pass in the QuickStartConnectivityService and

only acquire the NearbyConnectionsManager and QuickStartDecoder when

they are needed.

crrev.com/c/4616546 to validate Quick Start functionality.

entry.title: Split out SVG viewport resolution from SVGLengthContext
entry.content:
It's becoming more common to have a Length, or related, type that does

not need the whole SVGLengthContext machinery but only needs to be able

to resolve the viewport in order to resolve percentage values. Since

resolving the viewport requires access to the layout tree, there's also

no need to pass via the DOM node to perform the resolution.



Split out the SVGLengthContext's ResolveViewport() and

ViewportDimension() functions into a new SVGViewportResolver class that

performs this resolution. Make the main workhorse - ResolveViewport() -

walk the layout tree directly.



Convert some of the most obvious users (direct calls to

SVGLengthContext::ResolveViewport()). More conversions will be done in a

follow-up CL.

entry.title: [fyfre] Check if default browser callback is not null in handler
entry.content:
When opening chrome://intro/default-browser in the browser (not in the

FRE), in the first time HandleSetAsDefaultBrowser() and

HandleSkipDefaultBrowser() call the handler once callback, that is

IntroUI::HandleDefaultBrowserChoice().



IntroUI::SetDefaultBrowserCallback() is called by the FRE controller, so

when opened in the browser the UI callback is not set. Anyway

IntroUI::HandleDefaultBrowserChoice() checks if its callback is null or

not before running it, so it doesn't crash.



However, if any of the buttons were clicked before, when loading the

page again the handler callback is already used and is now null, so

clicking in any of the buttons would crash the browser. This CL adds a

check for the handler callback before running it.

entry.title: exo: Fixes for wl_output and xdg_output handling
entry.content:
Try to address several issues in the current `SendDisplayMetrics()`

implemetation:

- Clients using XdgOutput receive geometry and mode events twice. This

is unusual and breaks e.g. SDL2 based games, see the linked bug.

- Clients using XdgOutput do not receive scale changes.

- Refresh rate changes do not trigger a mode update.



Do so by more carefully evaluating `changed_metrics` and sending events

accordingly, as well only sending xdg output metrics in

`OnXdgOutputCreated()`.



This fixes crashes with the SDL2 Wayland backend and potentially other

clients.

entry.title: CrOS login: Allow tab traversal to "recover user" button
entry.content:
This commit allows users to traverse into the error bubble on the login

screen by pressing . Previously this wasn't possible: Pressing

while the password/pin input was focused did not immediately move

focus to the bubble, and the bubble would hide itself due to the

key press. This meant that even repeatedly pressing would not get

us into the bubble.



This commit explicitly changes the focus traversal order so that focus

moves immediately into the error bubble. We accomplish this by listening

to focus changes and acting accordingly when we notice traversal out of

the active input to elements that come after it in standard traversal

order (dropdown button, switch to password button).



Alternatives to this solution I've considered:



- Move the error bubble next to the active input element in the views

tree. This can work by manually implementing `Layout()` in the parent

of the input view, where we ignore the bubble. This fixes tab

traversal, but it breaks views::View hit box testing, so we can't

click the bubble anymore.

- Instead of checking for traversal between explicit elements on the

login screen, reimplement the views::View focus traversal logic with

our intended order (which doesn't entirely correspond to the views

tree). This would've involved non-trivial iteration through the views

tree and would thus be brittle.

- Using BubbleDialogDelegate to reimplement bubble. The standard views

logic considers such anchored bubbles in its focus traversal

algorithm. This would likely be a medium-sized project with open-ended

outcome, since it's not clear that we can replicate our current UI/UX

suing BubbleDialogDelegate, which is based on a separate Widget and

appears to be opinionated about its appearance:



https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:ui/views/bubble/bubble_dialog_delegate_view.h;l=248-250;drc=dad01b0ee94271b0336b87cfd0cfcc1e120ccc52

entry.title: Fix autocomplete wrt to AutofillPredictionsForAutocompleteUnrecognized.
entry.content:
Currently, autocomplete suggestions are shown if no field of the form

has a type. If at least a single field has an autofillable type,

autocomplete suggestions are suppressed.

In particular, if a form is fully annotated with

autocomplete=unrecognized, autocomplete suggestions are currently shown.

That's because autocomplete-the-feature ignores

autocomplete=unrecognized, while address Autofill gets disabled by it.



With AutofillPredictionsForAutocompleteUnrecognized,

autocomplete=unrecognized fields receive a type prediction. This breaks

the autocomplete suggestion behavior for forms fully annotated with

autocomplete=unrecognized. Since all fields now technically have a type,

autocomplete suggestions are no longer shown.

(For forms without predictions, e.g. because they are not address

related, nothing has changed)



This CL fixes this special case to keep the autocomplete suggestion

behavior consistent. This was requested by PMs in [1].

Since milestone 2 of manual fallbacks will change this behavior again,

the solution of this CL is not particularly pretty, but short.

entry.title: [signin] Fix crashes when reusing a signin tab
entry.content:
This CL fixes a issues when reusing a signin tab. In particular, the

`DiceTabHelper` is reset after sync was enabled, and it causes the

callbacks (enable_sync_callback_ and show_signin_error_callback_ to

be reset).



This causes crashes if the tab is later reused for another signin

event:

1) DCHECK in the constructor because of the missing error callback

2) crash if somehow the server would send a spurious ENABLE_SYNC

header. There is no reason the server would do this, but we should

still protect against this.



The fix is:

1) use the default error handling when the DiceTabHelper is reused

(same behavior as when there is no DiceTabHelper).

2) Ignore the ENABLE_SYNC directives from the server if there was no

flow in progress.



Fixed: 1471277

mode via debug shortcuts.
